-- Japan, India, Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-15T22:44:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-15/japan-india-malaysia-thailand-singapore-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise. Financial
markets in China are closed for the first three trading days of
this week and those in Taiwan are shut today.  
 Japan: The Ministry of Finance will sell 1.1 trillion yen
($12 billion) of 20-year bonds today. The results will be
announced at 12:45 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. The Trade Ministry is forecast
to report that Japan’s tertiary industry advanced 2.5 percent
in April after dropping 3 percent in March, according to the
median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey. The
report is due at 8:50 a.m.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.225 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 91.47 per dollar at 7:35 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 30 billion
rupees ($643 million) by selling treasury bills at an auction.
It will offer 20 billion rupees of 91-day securities and 10
billion rupees of 364-day notes.  
 The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.65
percent. The rupee was at 46.57.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 10 billion baht ($308
million) of bonds due 2015.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.25 percent. The baht was at 32.42 today.  
 Malaysia: The central bank plans to auction a combined 3
billion ringgit ($917 million) of 91- and 210-day debt. It will
also sell 500 million ringgit of 89-day Islamic notes.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.04 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2645 today.  
 Singapore: The government will report non-oil export data
for May tomorrow. Economists surveyed by Bloomberg News predict
a 25.7 percent increase from a year earlier, following a 29.4
percent gain in the previous month.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.58 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3913 today.  
 Philippines: The central bank will report overseas
remittances data for April. Cash transfers from Filipinos
abroad rose 5.6 percent to $1.55 billion in March.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent bond due February 2020 was
7.98 percent. The peso was at 46.45.  
